postcontent:

CMMG AR-15 M4 LE A3 Flat-Top Upper Assembly 300 AAC Blackout 1 in 7" Twist 16" Barrel Carbine Gas System WASP Melonite Finish CM with M4 Handguard, Single Rail Gas Block, Flash Hider
Product #: 892556 CMMG #: 30BF85F UPC #: REDACTED23

Product Information
 This CMMG AR-15 M4 LE Upper Assembly is chambered for the exciting new 300 AAC Blackout cartridge and is ready for instant, drop-in use on any standard small pin lower receiver. Perfect for a myriad of different uses from hunting, to personal defense, to competition or just plain fun, the 300 AAC Blackout offers shooters 30 caliber firepower in a standard AR-sized envelope. The M4 LE features a Forged 7075-T6 Aluminum A3 Flat-Top Receiver that is ideal for adding an optic and/or rear iron sight, and comes equipped with a 16" Medium Contour Barrel with a 1 in 7" twist for easy stabilization of heavy match projectiles. The upper comes complete with a receiver height single rail gas block, A2 flash hider, bolt carrier group, charging handle and M4-style polymer handguards. Magazine not included. 

The Chrome Moly Steel Barrel is finished inside and out with CMMG's durable Weapons Armament Surface Protection (WASP) Melonite treatment. The WASP Melonite process surface-hardens the metal, extending barrel service life by reducing friction in the bore and lessening bore surface wear. Also referred to as Salt Bath Nitriding, this treatment produces an extremely hard, slick surface on steel that resists carbon adhesion and increases corrosion resistance, making for easier cleaning and maintenance. Nitriding converts the steel's surface without any build-up, retaining all of the benefits of traditional chrome lining without suffering the accuracy degradation commonly encountered due to uneven application of chrome inside the barrel's bore. 

This 16" 300 AAC Blackout Upper utilizes the versatile Carbine Length Gas System, a good choice for this cartridge if various weights and types of ammunition are to be used. Most Subsonic and Supersonic loads, fired from either a Suppressed or Unsuppressed gun, are compatible with this configuration. However, some subsonic ammunition may not always cycle reliably under adverse conditions or in a severely fouled firearm without a sound suppressor attached to provide extra backpressure.

Pocket pistols and handguns geared towards concealed carry typically lack the features of their larger, easier to shoot service pistol counterparts. title: For Sale:  AK-74 with 2500 rounds, mags, accessories, etc.
postcontent:
The Gun:
Bulgarian AK-74 originally put together by Tennessee Guns International on a NoDak Spud receiver with quality K-VAR furniture and a surplus parts kit. It was struggling when I first got it (3-5 malfunctions per mag) so I sent it to a gunsmith who fixed it for me by replacing the barrel and some of the surplus parts. He said they jacked it up during initial manufacture. I don’t know anything but that it works fine now. Since then I’ve put about 2000 rounds through it with no issues. I have cleaned it within hours of every single time I’ve fired it. 
Mods I’ve done/had done to it:
The same gunsmith installed a scope side mount.
I installed a G2 trigger group and stainless steel shepherds crook.
I Dremmelled out a bolt-hold-back in the safety lever so I wouldn’t get yelled at when I was at the range.
Hogue grip (In my opinion, far superior to the Russian grip, which is like holding onto a broomstick. I can throw on a surplus or K-VAR grip if you don’t want it)

Since I got it fixed two years and ~2000 rounds ago this rifle has been 100% without malfunctions. I don’t shoot from a rest at paper much so I can’t give you MOAs or anything, but I could regularly ring a steel target at 200M while standing or prone, and that’s really all you can ask from an AK.

Magazines:
Four (4) Tapco 30-round magazines in various colors
Two (2) Tapco 10-round magaines
One (1) Promag 30-round magazine
Seven (7) surplus 30-round magazines
One (1) is an orange Bakelite (East German?), the rest are polymer (Bulgarian?).  Some have been painted with jungle green or OD Krylon.
One (1) Bulgarian Circle 10 45-round magazine

Some of them have numbers written on them in black or white paint pen so if I had a magazine-related issue I could write down or remember which one was giving me trouble. None of them ever had any issues.

Ammo:
330 7N6 on stripper clips
15 7N6 loose
115 Hornady V-MAX on stripper clips
2 sealed cans of 1080 7n6 (2160 rounds)

2620 total  rounds

Accessories:
30 15-round stripper clips
5 stripper clip spoons
UTG 5th generation double rail scope mount
Buttstock cleaning kit (rusty, never used)
Surplus leather sling
Bayonet with scabbard, frog, etc. (I’ve never been able to get it on the rifle. It’s definitely an AK-74 bayonet, but it might be that I’m just too retarded to make it work.)
Surplus 4-mag pouch
Surplus 2-mag pouch
Oiler
Official Soviet AK Manual

What I want:
I’m looking to switch straight-up from 5.45 to 7.62x39, so I’d like an AK-47. The following features are preferred:

Stamped receiver
G2 trigger
Bolt-hold-back on the safety lever
AK-74-style muzzle brake (will consider AKS-74U-style flash hider or even a slant brake)
Scope side mount
Quality K-VAR or polymer surplus furniture, fixed or side folding. I will consider wood. I will NOT consider fake “tactical” like Tapco, any wire/metal side or under folding stock, or a big cheese grater on the front.

Basically, if you have an Arsenal SLR-107, you have exactly what I want. Otherwise, send me the details and I will let you know.

I also want magazines (metal and polymer surplus preferred) of any and all sizes (5, 10, 20, 30, 40, 75, etc.), ammo (steel, brass, FMJ, HP, AP, paper patched, I don’t care), and accessories (bayonet, sling, pouches, stripper clip spoons, etc).

I DO NOT want to split this up since I’m getting out of 5.45mm. Trade value is $1500. I would much prefer to trade it rather than sell it, unless you can make me a sweet offer. I am a KY resident (stationed at Fort Campbell), so we will need to meet at a gun store and get a NICS check to transfer. I have a concealed carry permit.
